    <name>
      <text>Circle Equation with Center on a Given Line</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Consider a circle that passes through the points \( \text{A} ({@x_1@} \, , \, {@y_1@} )\) and \( \text{B}({@x_2@} \, , \, {@y_2@} )\) and has its center located on the line with the equation \( {@expr@} \) .</p>
<p><b>1.</b> Find the center of the circle</p>
<p> Center \(=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</p>
<p><b>2.</b> Find the radius of the circle</p>
<p> Radius \(=\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]</p>
<p><b>3.</b> Give the equation  of the circle</p>
<p> Equation \(:\) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]][[feedback:prt3]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked Solution</h3>
<p>To find an equation of the circle passing through the points \( \text{A} ({@x_1@} ,  {@y_1@} )\) and \( \text{B}({@x_2@}  , {@y_2@} )\) with its center on the line  \( {@expr@} \) , we can follow these steps: </p>
<p><b>Step 1:</b> Finding \(OA^2\) and \(OB^2\):</p>
<p>Let the center of the circle be \(O(h\, , \, k)\). We need to use the formula of distance to get  \( O\, A^2\) and \( O B^2\) involving \(h\) and \(k\). The distance between two points is given by:</p>
<p>\(\text{Distance}^2=(x_2-x_1)^2+(y_2-y_1)^2\)</p>
<p>For points \(A ( {@x_1@} \, , \, {@y_1@} )\) and \(O(h,k)\):</p>
<p>\(
\begin{align}
OA^2 & =(h -({@x_1@}))^2+(k- ({@y_1@}) )^2 \\
 &= {@expand((h -x_1)^2+(k- y_1 )^2)@}
\end{align}
\)</p>
<p></p>

<p>For points \(B({@x_2@} \, , \, {@y_2@} )\) and \(O(h,k)\):</p>
<p>\(
\begin{align}
OB^2 & =(h-({@x_2@}) )^2+(k-({@y_2@}) )^2 \\
& ={@expand((h-x_2 )^2+(k-y_2 )^2)@}
\end{align}
\)</p>
<p><b>Step 2:</b> Determining the expression of \(h\):</p>
<p>Since \(O A^2=O B^2\), we can set up the following equation:</p>
<p>\({@sim@}\)</p>
<p> \( h={@h_val@} \)</p>
<p><b>Step 3:</b> Determining the coordinates of the centre: </p>
<p>Since the center \(O(h\, , \, k)\) lies on the line \( {@expr@} \), we can substitute \(x\) and \(y\) by  \(h\) and \(k\) respectively into this equation, that is, \( {@ gradient*h-k+(k_fval-gradient*h_fval)=0 @} \).</p>
<p>Substituting \(h={@h_val@} \) in \( {@ gradient*h-k+(k_fval-gradient*h_fval)=0 @} \), gives \( {@gradient@} {@h_val@}-k+{@(k_fval-gradient*h_fval)=0@}  \). Thus \(k={@k_fval@}\).</p>

<p>Substituting back for \(k\) in \(h={@h_val@} \), yields to \( h={@h_fval@} \).</p>
<p>Hence the center of the circle is \(O({@h_fval@} , {@k_fval@})\)</p>

<p><b>Step 4:</b> Finding the radius:</p>
<p>Now, let's find the radius of the circle using the distance formula between center \(O({@h_fval@} , {@k_fval@})\) and point \( \text{A} ({@x_1@} \, , \, {@y_1@} )\):</p>
<p>We recall \( \text{radius} =\sqrt{(x_2-x_1)^2+ (y_2 - y_1)^2} \)</p>
<p>
\( 
\begin{align}
             \text{radius}   &= \sqrt{(h-({@x_1@}))^2+ (k - ({@y_1@}))^2} \\
               &= \sqrt{({@h_fval@}-({@x_1@}))^2+ ({@k_fval@} - ({@y_1@}))^2} \\
               &=\sqrt{ ({@h_fval-x_1@})^2+ ({@k_fval - y_1@})^2} \\
               &= \sqrt{ {@(h_fval-x_1)^2 @}+ {@(k_fval - y_1)^2@} } \\
               &=\sqrt{  {@(h_fval-x_1)^2 + (k_fval - y_1)^2@} } \\
              &={@ta2@}
\end{align} 
\)
</p>
<p><b>Step 5:</b> Writing the equation of the Circle:</p>
<p>Now that we have the center \(O({@h_fval@}\, , \, {@k_fval@}) \) and the radius \({@rad_sq@} \), we use the equation of a circle: \((x-h)^2+(y-k)^2=r^2\). </p>
<p>Substituting the corresponding values of \(h,\, k\) and \(r\) we get, \({@ta3@}\), which can be written as: \({@expand((x-h_fval)^2+(y-k_fval)^2-rad_sq)=0@}\)</p>]]></text>
